Hi,

&gt; I have some default submodules , shall I delete them ? won&#39;t that take 
&gt; me into trap of infinite-loop ?
&gt; 
&gt; &lt;newObject name=&quot;acceptIfSurtPrefixed&quot; 
&gt; class=&quot;org.archive.crawler.deciderules.SurtPrefixedDecideRule&quot;&gt;
&gt; &lt;string name=&quot;decision&quot;&gt;ACCEPT&lt;/string&gt;
&gt; &lt;string name=&quot;surts-source-file&quot;/&gt;
&gt; &lt;boolean name=&quot;seeds-as-surt-prefixes&quot;&gt;true&lt;/boolean&gt;
&gt; &lt;string name=&quot;surts-dump-file&quot;/&gt;
&gt; &lt;boolean name=&quot;also-check-via&quot;&gt;false&lt;/boolean&gt;
&gt; &lt;boolean name=&quot;rebuild-on-reconfig&quot;&gt;true&lt;/boolean&gt;
&gt; &lt;/newObject&gt;

I think the rule above can be safely removed.


&gt; &lt;newObject name=&quot;rejectIfTooManyHops&quot; 
&gt; class=&quot;org.archive.crawler.deciderules.TooManyHopsDecideRule&quot;&gt;
&gt; &lt;integer name=&quot;max-hops&quot;&gt;20&lt;/integer&gt;
&gt; &lt;/newObject&gt;

You can safely keep this one.


&gt; &lt;newObject name=&quot;acceptIfTranscluded&quot; 
&gt; class=&quot;org.archive.crawler.deciderules.TransclusionDecideRule&quot;&gt;
&gt; &lt;integer name=&quot;max-trans-hops&quot;&gt;3&lt;/integer&gt;
&gt; &lt;integer name=&quot;max-speculative-hops&quot;&gt;1&lt;/integer&gt;
&gt; &lt;/newObject&gt;

This one should definitely be removed as you don&#39;t want images and other 
stuff from other domains.


&gt; &lt;newObject name=&quot;rejectIfPathological&quot; 
&gt; class=&quot;org.archive.crawler.deciderules.PathologicalPathDecideRule&quot;&gt;
&gt; &lt;integer name=&quot;max-repetitions&quot;&gt;2&lt;/integer&gt;
&gt; &lt;/newObject&gt;

You can safely keep this one.


&gt; &lt;newObject name=&quot;rejectIfTooManyPathSegs&quot; 
&gt; class=&quot;org.archive.crawler.deciderules.TooManyPathSegmentsDecideRule&quot;&gt;
&gt; &lt;integer name=&quot;max-path-depth&quot;&gt;20&lt;/integer&gt;
&gt; &lt;/newObject&gt;

This can also be kept in a chain.

&gt; I add the matches in a list , is there any difference ?
&gt; 
&gt; &lt;newObject name=&quot;acceptPaths&quot; 
&gt; class=&quot;org.archive.crawler.deciderules.MatchesListRegExpDecideRule&quot;&gt;
&gt; &lt;string name=&quot;decision&quot;&gt;ACCEPT&lt;/string&gt;
&gt; &lt;string name=&quot;list-logic&quot;&gt;OR&lt;/string&gt;
&gt; &#8722;
&gt; &lt;stringList name=&quot;regexp-list&quot;&gt;
&gt; &lt;string&gt;.*/home&#92;?page=.*&lt;/string&gt;
&gt; &lt;string&gt;http://www&#92;.citeulike&#92;.org/tag/.*&lt;/string&gt;
&gt; &lt;string&gt;http://www&#92;.citeulike&#92;.org/user/.*&lt;/string&gt;
&gt; &lt;string&gt;.*/article/[0-9]*$&lt;/string&gt;
&gt; &lt;/stringList&gt;
&gt; &lt;/newObject&gt;
&gt; 
&gt; I add REject
&gt; 
&gt; &lt;newObject name=&quot;rejectPath&quot; 
&gt; class=&quot;org.archive.crawler.deciderules.NotMatchesRegExpDecideRule&quot;&gt;
&gt; &lt;string name=&quot;decision&quot;&gt;REJECT&lt;/string&gt;
&gt; &lt;string name=&quot;regexp&quot;&gt;.*www.citeulike.org.*&lt;/string&gt;
&gt; &lt;/newObject&gt;
&gt; &#8722;
&gt; &lt;newObject name=&quot;reject&quot; 
&gt; class=&quot;org.archive.crawler.deciderules.MatchesListRegExpDecideRule&quot;&gt;
&gt; &lt;string name=&quot;decision&quot;&gt;REJECT&lt;/string&gt;
&gt; &lt;string name=&quot;list-logic&quot;&gt;OR&lt;/string&gt;
&gt; &#8722;
&gt; &lt;stringList name=&quot;regexp-list&quot;&gt;
&gt; &lt;string&gt;http://www&#92;.citeulike&#92;.org/user/.*/.*&lt;/string&gt;
&gt; &lt;string&gt;http://www&#92;.citeulike&#92;.org/pdf_options/.*&lt;/string&gt;
&gt; &lt;string&gt;http://www&#92;.citeulike&#92;.org/groups/.*&lt;/string&gt;
&gt; &lt;/stringList&gt;
&gt; &lt;/newObject&gt;

IMO this gives the same result and is even less verbose.
Looks quite nice.


&gt; the crawling seems to be slower than before .

How do you estimate the speed?
The process is very slow on my machine due to the politenes policy which 
  enforces pauses between requests to the same host. And we are actualy 
crawling only one host.

You can tune frontier/delay-factor parameter in the job settings to 
increase speed a little bit.

Best,
Sergey
